  <mods:abstract>Drinking water sources in the United States contain contaminants exceeding legal limits and threatening public health (Harloe 2017; Denchak 2018). A study reported in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences found that, in 2015, the water quality of nine percent of nationally sampled city water systems—91 million citizens—violated standards of the Safe Drinking Water Act (Allairea, Wu, and Lall 2018). Why are such violations permitted by government? Has government failed to protect citizens?Theoretical motivation for this study is rooted in Freudenburg’s (1993) concept of “recreancy,” the failure of government institutions to discharge their responsibilities to citizens appropriately and reliably. Researchers have documented recreancy in institutional responses to disasters such as the 1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill (Picou, Marshall, and Gill 2004) and the 2005 Hurricane Katrina (Gill 2007). However, it remains unclear what routine behaviors in government institutions lead to failure.</mods:abstract>
